22
00:01:44,560 --> 00:01:47,358
See this bunch
of Mickey Mouse sweatshirts?

23
00:01:47,440 --> 00:01:50,193
That's the tour from China,
connecting to Orlando.

24
00:01:50,280 --> 00:01:52,874
When was the last time
you saw Chinese tourists

25
00:01:52,960 --> 00:01:56,509
on their way to Disney World
without any cameras?

26
00:01:56,600 --> 00:01:59,398
Possible forged documents
on 10 and 11.

27
00:01:59,480 --> 00:02:01,391
[Shouting]

28
00:02:07,120 --> 00:02:10,192
Sir. Sir. Passport.

29
00:02:12,400 --> 00:02:13,674
Thank you.

30
00:02:14,680 --> 00:02:17,956
Welcome, Mr. Navorski.

31
00:02:18,040 --> 00:02:19,951
Purpose of your visit?

32
00:02:20,040 --> 00:02:23,874
- [Speaks Bulgarian]
- Business or pleasure?

33
00:02:23,960 --> 00:02:25,871
[Speaks Bulgarian]

34
00:02:27,760 --> 00:02:29,671
<i>[Beeps]</i>

35
00:02:37,800 --> 00:02:39,518
Sir, I have an IBIS hit on six.

36
00:02:39,600 --> 00:02:40,953
[Man] No!

37
00:02:41,040 --> 00:02:44,316
Mr. Navorski, please follow me.

38
00:02:44,400 --> 00:02:48,075
<i>[Tannoy]
... flight number 746 from Montreal</i>

39
00:02:48,160 --> 00:02:51,675
<i>must proceed to US Immigration
before claiming their luggage.</i>

40
00:02:51,760 --> 00:02:55,912
All right, Mr. Navorski,
we'd like you to wait here, please.

41
00:02:56,000 --> 00:02:57,274
Next, please.

42
00:02:57,360 --> 00:02:58,839
Next, please.

43
00:03:03,960 --> 00:03:05,678
[Electric razor]

44
00:03:13,520 --> 00:03:16,830
<i>[Thurman] What are you doing
in the United States, Mr. Navorski?</i>

45
00:03:21,800 --> 00:03:24,553
[Thick Bulgarian accent]
Yellow taxicab, please.

46
00:03:24,640 --> 00:03:27,837
Take me to Ramada Inn,

47
00:03:27,920 --> 00:03:31,435
161 Lexington.

48
00:03:35,160 --> 00:03:37,310
Staying at the Ramada Inn?

49
00:03:37,400 --> 00:03:39,789
Keep the change.

50
00:03:39,880 --> 00:03:43,111
Do you know anyone in New York?

51
00:03:43,200 --> 00:03:44,633
Yes.

52
00:03:44,720 --> 00:03:47,473
- Who?
- Yes.

53
00:03:48,400 --> 00:03:52,188
- Who?
- Yes.

54
00:03:52,280 --> 00:03:55,397
- No, do you know anyone in New York?
- Yes.

55
00:03:55,480 --> 00:03:57,391
- Who?
- Yes.

56
00:04:02,480 --> 00:04:04,755
161 Lexington.

57
00:04:04,840 --> 00:04:08,355
OK, Mr. Navorski, I need to see
your return ticket, please.

58
00:04:09,640 --> 00:04:12,108
No, your return ticket. Your...

59
00:04:12,200 --> 00:04:14,395
- Oh... Yes.
- Ah.

60
00:04:15,200 --> 00:04:17,509
[Woman screams]

61
00:04:17,600 --> 00:04:19,511
This is just a standard procedure.

62
00:04:20,840 --> 00:04:23,718
I'm going to need the passport also.

63
00:04:23,800 --> 00:04:25,631
Oh... OK.

64
00:04:25,720 --> 00:04:27,278
- No, no.
- Thank you.

65
00:04:27,360 --> 00:04:28,873
Mr. Navorski.

66
00:04:30,360 --> 00:04:32,874
That. Passport.

67
00:04:35,600 --> 00:04:37,511
That.

68
00:04:43,080 --> 00:04:45,275
Mr. Navorski?
Sorry to keep you waiting.

69
00:04:45,360 --> 00:04:50,514
I'm Frank Dixon, Director of Customs
and Border Protection here at JFK.

70
00:04:50,600 --> 00:04:53,353
I help people
with their immigration problems.

71
00:04:53,440 --> 00:04:56,079
We're looking for
an interpreter for you.

72
00:04:56,160 --> 00:04:59,914
How are we doing on that?
Do we have an interpreter?

73
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:02,878
But I understand
that you speak a little English.

74
00:05:02,960 --> 00:05:05,599
- Yes.
- You do?

75
00:05:05,680 --> 00:05:08,956
I hope you don't mind if I eat
while we talk. I've a bit of bad news.

76
00:05:09,040 --> 00:05:11,952
Your country has suspended
all traveling privileges

77
00:05:12,040 --> 00:05:14,600
on passports issued
by your government.

78
00:05:14,680 --> 00:05:17,592
And our State Department
has revoked the visa

79
00:05:17,680 --> 00:05:20,069
that was going to allow you
to enter the US.

80
00:05:20,160 --> 00:05:22,833
That's it in a nutshell, basically.

81
00:05:22,920 --> 00:05:27,152
While you were in the air there
was a military coup in your country.

82
00:05:27,240 --> 00:05:30,232
Most of the dead were members
of the Presidential Guard.

83
00:05:30,320 --> 00:05:32,754
They were attacked
in the middle of the night.

84
00:05:32,840 --> 00:05:35,070
They got it all on GHN, I think.

85
00:05:35,160 --> 00:05:38,516
There were few civilian casualties.
I'm sure your family's fine.

86
00:05:38,600 --> 00:05:42,354
Mr. Navorski, your country
was annexed from the inside.

87
00:05:42,440 --> 00:05:45,000
The Republic of Krakozhia
is under new leadership.

88
00:05:45,080 --> 00:05:47,913
Krakozhia. Krakozhia

89
00:05:49,480 --> 00:05:54,998
- Krakozhia.
- Right. I don't think he gets it.

90
00:05:55,080 --> 00:05:58,197
Er... Let me... OK. Look.

91
00:05:58,280 --> 00:06:00,714
Imagine that these potato chips
are Krakozhia.

92
00:06:00,800 --> 00:06:03,030
Kra-kozhia.

93
00:06:03,120 --> 00:06:04,553
- Kra-kozhia.
- Yes.

94
00:06:04,640 --> 00:06:06,551
- Krakozhia.
- OK.

95
00:06:06,640 --> 00:06:10,474
Er... So the potato chips are Krakozhia.

96
00:06:10,560 --> 00:06:14,075
- And this apple...
- Big Apple. Big Apple.

97
00:06:14,160 --> 00:06:16,833
...Big Apple represents
the Liberty Rebels.

98
00:06:17,600 --> 00:06:19,511
OK?

99
00:06:20,800 --> 00:06:23,473
No more Krakozhia! OK?

100
00:06:23,560 --> 00:06:28,111
New government.
Revolution. You understand?

101
00:06:28,200 --> 00:06:31,397
All the flights in and out
of your country have been suspended.

102
00:06:31,480 --> 00:06:35,439
The new government has sealed all
borders, so your visa's no longer valid.

103
00:06:35,520 --> 00:06:38,990
So, currently
you are a citizen of nowhere.

104
00:06:39,080 --> 00:06:40,991
Now, we can't process you new papers

105
00:06:41,080 --> 00:06:46,837
until the US recognizes your country's
new diplomatic reclassification.

106
00:06:46,920 --> 00:06:49,434
You don't qualify for asylum,
refugee status,

107
00:06:49,520 --> 00:06:52,273
temporary protective status,
humanitarian parole,

108
00:06:52,360 --> 00:06:56,273
or non-immigration work travel.
You don't qualify for any of these.

109
00:06:56,360 --> 00:06:58,316
You are at this time simply...

110
00:07:00,600 --> 00:07:04,036
...unacceptable.
- Unacceptable.

111
00:07:04,120 --> 00:07:06,350
- Unacceptable.
- Unacceptable.

112
00:07:06,440 --> 00:07:13,039
<i>Big Apple tour includes Brooklyn Bridge,
Empire State, Broadway show Cats.</i>

113
00:07:13,120 --> 00:07:16,237
<i>I got more bad news for you.
Cats has closed.</i>

114
00:07:16,320 --> 00:07:18,117
OK. OK.

115
00:07:18,200 --> 00:07:21,112
Now I go New York City. Thank you.

116
00:07:21,200 --> 00:07:25,193
No, Mr. Navorski. I cannot allow you
to enter the United States at this time.

117
00:07:25,280 --> 00:07:28,670
- Krakozhia.
- We can't allow you to go home either.

118
00:07:28,760 --> 00:07:32,355
You don't really have a home.
Technically it doesn't exist.

119
00:07:32,440 --> 00:07:37,719
<i>It's like a Twilight Zone.
Do you get that show over there?</i>

120
00:07:37,800 --> 00:07:40,951
<i>Talking Tina, Zanti Misfits.</i>

121
00:07:41,040 --> 00:07:43,349
<i>Zanti Misfits was Outer Limits, sir.</i>

122
00:07:43,440 --> 00:07:45,317
Really? It's not important.

123
00:07:45,400 --> 00:07:48,676
Where do I buy the Nike shoes?

124
00:07:48,760 --> 00:07:51,274
OK, Mr. Navorski, come here.

125
00:07:51,360 --> 00:07:53,510
Here's my dilemma, Mr. Navorski.

126
00:07:53,600 --> 00:07:57,275
You have no right to enter the US
and I have no right to detain you.

127
00:07:57,360 --> 00:07:59,749
You have fallen through
a crack in the system.

128
00:07:59,840 --> 00:08:03,594
- I am crack.
- Yes. Until we get this sorted out,

129
00:08:03,680 --> 00:08:07,753
I will allow you to enter
the International Transit Lounge.

130
00:08:07,840 --> 00:08:11,276
I'm going to sign a release form
that is going to make you a free man.

131
00:08:11,360 --> 00:08:13,476
- Free?
- Free. Free.

132
00:08:13,560 --> 00:08:19,351
Free to go anywhere you like
in the International Transit Lounge.

133
00:08:19,440 --> 00:08:21,351
- OK?
- OK.

134
00:08:21,440 --> 00:08:23,715
- OK.
- OK.

135
00:08:23,800 --> 00:08:24,869
OK.

136
00:08:24,960 --> 00:08:27,520
Uncle Sam will have this
sorted out by tomorrow,

137
00:08:27,600 --> 00:08:30,034
and welcome
to the United States. Almost.

138
00:08:30,120 --> 00:08:31,394
[Dixon laughs]

139
00:08:31,480 --> 00:08:33,471
- Thank you.
- OK. All right.

140
00:08:33,560 --> 00:08:35,471
Thanks, Judge.

141
00:08:39,080 --> 00:08:40,991
[Door closes]

142
00:08:51,880 --> 00:08:55,839
<i>[Tannoy] Announcing the arrival
of flight 76 from Singapore Airlines.</i>

143
00:08:55,920 --> 00:08:57,831
Now, Mr. Navorski.

144
00:08:57,920 --> 00:08:59,592
Mr. Navorski. Mr. Navorski.

145
00:08:59,680 --> 00:09:02,148
This is the International
Transit Lounge.

146
00:09:02,240 --> 00:09:05,198
You are free to wait here.
These are food vouchers.

147
00:09:05,280 --> 00:09:09,398
You can use them in the Food Court.
Your Krakozhian money is no good here.

148
00:09:09,480 --> 00:09:12,278
This is a 15-minute,
prepaid calling card.

149
00:09:12,360 --> 00:09:14,590
You may call home, if you like.

150
00:09:14,680 --> 00:09:18,593
This, in case we need to contact you,
is a pager.

151
00:09:18,680 --> 00:09:21,877
You must keep this
with you at all times.

152
00:09:21,960 --> 00:09:27,353
Here is an ID badge for you
to get into CBP. Beyond those doors...

153
00:09:27,440 --> 00:09:31,035
Mr. Navorski.
I'm going to need you to look at me.

154
00:09:31,120 --> 00:09:33,759
Beyond those doors is American soil.

155
00:09:33,840 --> 00:09:36,354
Mr. Dixon wants me to make it clear

156
00:09:36,440 --> 00:09:39,113
that you are not
to enter through those doors.

157
00:09:39,200 --> 00:09:43,398
You are not to leave this building.
America is closed.

158
00:09:43,480 --> 00:09:45,391
America closed.

159
00:09:46,640 --> 00:09:48,437
What I do?

160
00:09:49,600 --> 00:09:53,115
There's only one thing
you can do here, Mr. Navorski.

161
00:09:53,200 --> 00:09:55,430
Shop.

162
00:09:55,520 --> 00:09:59,752
<i>[Tannoy] Passengers of flight 854
New York/Warsaw...</i>

163
00:09:59,840 --> 00:10:01,751
<i>[TV: Brass band plays]</i>

164
00:10:06,520 --> 00:10:10,672
<i>[TV]... the international community
tries to secure a peaceful resolution.</i>

165
00:10:10,760 --> 00:10:14,992
<i>The populace has to wonder if
they will ever find political stability,</i>

166
00:10:15,080 --> 00:10:20,234
<i>or find the leadership to secure
their place on the world stage.</i>

167
00:10:20,320 --> 00:10:22,880
<i>And next this hour,
looking to buy a 90-foot yacht?</i>

168
00:10:29,040 --> 00:10:32,953
<i>[TV]... taken hostage. We're hearing
that the Vice President has been killed</i>

169
00:10:33,040 --> 00:10:37,192
<i>along with four cabinet members,
13 injured soldiers and 20 civilians.</i>

170
00:10:37,280 --> 00:10:40,317
<i>By dawn, rebel leaders
had surrounded the state houses.</i>

171
00:10:40,400 --> 00:10:44,188
<i>In a symbolic gesture, the national flag
of Krakozhia was torn down</i>

172
00:10:44,280 --> 00:10:47,317
<i>from the Presidential Palace
and the parliament building.</i>

173
00:11:12,080 --> 00:11:13,991
Please. Please.

174
00:11:14,840 --> 00:11:16,239
Television.

175
00:11:16,320 --> 00:11:18,231
[Speaks Bulgarian]

176
00:11:20,880 --> 00:11:23,952
<i>[Tannoy] Passenger Chen Wan-Shiu
and Liu Tao-Jing,</i>

177
00:11:24,040 --> 00:11:27,271
<i>please come to podium
to pick up your boarding passes.</i>

178
00:11:35,400 --> 00:11:37,311
[Speaks Bulgarian]

179
00:11:40,800 --> 00:11:45,794
<i>This just in. Last night a military coup
overthrew the government of Krakozhia.</i>

180
00:11:45,880 --> 00:11:48,599
<i>Bombing and gunfire
were heard through the night.</i>

181
00:11:48,680 --> 00:11:50,716
<i>Although details are unclear,</i>

182
00:11:50,800 --> 00:11:56,033
<i>we are told that President Vagobagin
and his aides have been taken hostage.</i>

183
00:11:56,120 --> 00:11:58,953
<i>Bonjour, monsieur.
You are a Red Carpet Club member?</i>

184
00:11:59,760 --> 00:12:01,318
[Speaks Bulgarian]

185
00:12:01,400 --> 00:12:05,313
I need to see
your boarding pass and club card, sir.

186
00:12:05,400 --> 00:12:08,437
I'm sorry, sir.
This is a private lounge.

187
00:12:08,520 --> 00:12:11,717
The public lounge is downstairs.

188
00:12:13,240 --> 00:12:18,758
<i>[TV] The tiniest nation in the region
has been shaken by another uprising.</i>

189
00:12:18,840 --> 00:12:23,470
<i>Krakozhia has been involved in civil war
throughout the late '80s and '90s</i>

190
00:12:23,560 --> 00:12:26,438
<i>as it has tried
to transition from Communist rule.</i>

191
00:12:51,440 --> 00:12:53,351
- Watch it!
- Please.

192
00:12:54,720 --> 00:12:56,631
Please, telephone?
Telephone?

193
00:12:57,680 --> 00:12:59,591
Telephone?

194
00:13:02,320 --> 00:13:03,878
Please. Please.

195
00:13:03,960 --> 00:13:05,871
Please. Please.

196
00:13:35,360 --> 00:13:39,399
<i>[Tannoy] For security reasons, please
keep your luggage with you at all times.</i>

197
00:13:39,480 --> 00:13:44,270
<i>Unattended luggage will be removed
for inspection and may be destroyed.</i>

198
00:13:49,080 --> 00:13:50,991
[Speaks Bulgarian]

199
00:13:58,320 --> 00:14:02,836
Oh, my God.
Oh, my God, you broke my bag!

200
00:14:02,920 --> 00:14:06,515
I got this in Paris.
This is my favorite bag.

201
00:14:06,600 --> 00:14:11,594
I can't believe you just broke my bag!
Mom, Dad! He broke my bag!

202
00:14:20,600 --> 00:14:25,151
- Food document.
- Excuse me. Stop it. Stop it.

203
00:14:25,240 --> 00:14:27,629
Do you have an appointment?

204
00:14:27,720 --> 00:14:33,397
I don't let anyone to look
at my trash without an appointment.

205
00:14:33,480 --> 00:14:36,358
I have an opening next Tuesday.

206
00:14:36,440 --> 00:14:40,194
Tuesday. Tuesday,
Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Tuesday.

207
00:14:40,280 --> 00:14:43,875
It will be good time for you
to come back and get lost.

208
00:14:43,960 --> 00:14:46,235
OK, goodbye. Sorry.

209
00:14:47,960 --> 00:14:49,916
Tuesday.

210
00:14:50,680 --> 00:14:53,877
<i>[Strangers In The Night instrumental
plays]</i>

211
00:15:11,160 --> 00:15:13,071
[Airplane descends]

212
00:15:48,360 --> 00:15:50,271
[Yawns]

213
00:16:42,440 --> 00:16:43,555
[Strains]

214
00:17:03,720 --> 00:17:05,631
[Fizzes]

215
00:17:37,320 --> 00:17:39,231
[Sighs]

216
00:17:39,320 --> 00:17:40,878
[Engine screams]

217
00:17:41,880 --> 00:17:43,791
Don't shoot!

218
00:17:51,360 --> 00:17:56,718
[Salchak] She sleeps 12, Frank. Has a
120-volt generator, wet bar, gas range.

219
00:17:56,800 --> 00:17:58,677
She looks amazing.

220
00:17:58,760 --> 00:18:01,228
She's my pot of gold
at the end of the rainbow.

221
00:18:01,320 --> 00:18:04,073
She's a beautiful boat
and I hope you get her soon.

222
00:18:04,160 --> 00:18:07,152
- You've earned her.
- Thank you, Frank.

223
00:18:07,240 --> 00:18:09,879
- You have.
- Actually, I bought her yesterday.

224
00:18:09,960 --> 00:18:12,838
Come on. Congratulations!

225
00:18:12,920 --> 00:18:15,434
I'm nominating you to take my place.

226
00:18:16,120 --> 00:18:19,556
You will assume the duties
of acting Field Commissioner

227
00:18:19,640 --> 00:18:22,313
until you get approval from Washington.

228
00:18:22,400 --> 00:18:24,789
Really? I don't know what to say.

229
00:18:25,680 --> 00:18:29,150
- Jesus. Richard, is this real?
- It's real, Frank, it's real.

230
00:18:29,240 --> 00:18:31,629
Don't pretend to be surprised.

231
00:18:33,520 --> 00:18:36,956
You've been waiting for me to retire
or drop dead for years now.

232
00:18:37,040 --> 00:18:39,634
No, I haven't been
waiting for you to retire.

233
00:18:39,720 --> 00:18:41,597
[Both laugh]

234
00:18:41,680 --> 00:18:43,159
That's all right, Frank.

235
00:18:43,240 --> 00:18:46,755
My retirement will become official
the day you get sworn in.

236
00:18:49,880 --> 00:18:53,668
- You've waited a long time for this.
- I have.

237
00:18:53,760 --> 00:18:57,230
Just be careful
about the inspection process.

238
00:18:57,320 --> 00:19:00,232
I will.
I've been here for 17 years...

239
00:19:00,320 --> 00:19:03,392
We're talking about
the Field Commissioner position.

240
00:19:03,480 --> 00:19:07,632
People are going to look to you
for leadership, to set an example.

241
00:19:09,720 --> 00:19:11,870
What are you saying?

242
00:19:11,960 --> 00:19:13,837
[Chuckles]

243
00:19:13,920 --> 00:19:17,276
I'm saying the job is yours to lose.

244
00:19:17,360 --> 00:19:21,512
Ship the Colombians
off to asylum hearings,

245
00:19:21,600 --> 00:19:24,194
and call the parents
of those kids from Long Island.

246
00:19:24,280 --> 00:19:27,078
Tell them it was a bad idea
to let them go to Jamaica.

247
00:19:27,160 --> 00:19:30,391
Come on, let's go. South America
and Madrid are on the tarmac.

248
00:19:30,480 --> 00:19:32,675
I want them out of here in half an hour.

249
00:19:36,960 --> 00:19:39,474
Mr. Thurman.

250
00:19:39,560 --> 00:19:43,678
There's a man walking around
the terminal in a bathrobe.

251
00:19:43,760 --> 00:19:47,196
I know, sir. You put him there.

252
00:20:06,200 --> 00:20:08,156
Welcome to the United States.

253
00:20:08,240 --> 00:20:09,753
Next!

254
00:20:09,840 --> 00:20:11,751
[Speaks Bulgarian]

255
00:20:13,320 --> 00:20:14,912
I need visa.

256
00:20:15,000 --> 00:20:18,356
Where's your green form?
I can't do anything without it.

257
00:20:18,440 --> 00:20:20,317
Go to the wall.

258
00:20:20,400 --> 00:20:21,833
Next!

259
00:20:24,080 --> 00:20:25,798
Sir.

260
00:20:28,760 --> 00:20:31,228
The light green form.

261
00:20:34,040 --> 00:20:37,715
<i># I love New York...</i>

262
00:20:37,800 --> 00:20:40,155
<i>- I love it!
- # New York</i>

263
00:20:41,840 --> 00:20:46,470
<i># I love New York</i>

264
00:20:47,680 --> 00:20:51,878
<i># I love New York...</i>

265
00:20:56,680 --> 00:20:58,910
Light green.

266
00:21:01,040 --> 00:21:04,271
Mr. Navorski, you cannot
get into New York without a visa.

267
00:21:04,360 --> 00:21:06,476
You cannot get a visa
without a passport,

268
00:21:06,560 --> 00:21:09,233
and you cannot get
a new passport without a country.

269
00:21:09,320 --> 00:21:11,788
There's nothing
we can do for you here.

270
00:21:11,880 --> 00:21:13,791
I give you light green.

271
00:21:13,880 --> 00:21:16,997
I'm sorry,
but you've wasted an entire day.

272
00:21:17,080 --> 00:21:18,991
At this time you are simply...

273
00:21:20,440 --> 00:21:22,908
- Unacceptable.
- Yes.

274
00:21:23,000 --> 00:21:24,035
Unacceptable.

275
00:21:24,120 --> 00:21:26,031
[Snoring]

276
00:21:26,120 --> 00:21:27,872
[Frank] Why is he still here?

277
00:21:27,960 --> 00:21:32,033
You released him, sir.
You put him there.

278
00:21:32,120 --> 00:21:35,908
Why doesn't he walk out the doors?
Why doesn't he try to escape?

279
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:40,755
- Sir, you told him to wait.
- I didn't think he'd actually do it.

280
00:21:43,480 --> 00:21:47,029
I mean, he's in a crack.
Who the hell waits in a crack?

281
00:21:47,120 --> 00:21:51,398
No news from the State Department,
but we can deport him in a few days.

282
00:21:51,480 --> 00:21:55,029
Yeah, it could be a few days.
It could be a week, two weeks, a month.

283
00:21:55,120 --> 00:21:58,749
Who knows what this guy is thinking,
what gulag he escaped from.

284
00:21:58,840 --> 00:22:00,751
[Woman] Next!

285
00:22:02,880 --> 00:22:05,110
Everything he does comes back to me.

286
00:22:05,200 --> 00:22:08,909
- You want him back in the holding cell?
- No, I'll show him the door.

287
00:22:11,040 --> 00:22:12,439
Hello.

288
00:22:13,440 --> 00:22:15,351
Hello.

289
00:22:16,200 --> 00:22:19,590
- Do you have an appointment?
- Yes. 9.30.

290
00:22:19,680 --> 00:22:22,797
Food document, trash. Tuesday.

291
00:22:22,880 --> 00:22:26,156
Tuesday. I hate the Tuesday.

292
00:22:26,240 --> 00:22:27,673
Excuse me.

293
00:22:32,520 --> 00:22:34,431
[Man speaks German]

294
00:22:35,560 --> 00:22:37,471
[Speaks Bulgarian]

295
00:22:53,080 --> 00:22:56,959
Airports are tricky places,
Mr. Navorski.

296
00:22:57,040 --> 00:22:59,679
I'm about to tell you something.

297
00:22:59,760 --> 00:23:02,320
Something you can
never repeat to anyone.

298
00:23:02,400 --> 00:23:04,994
Do you understand? It's a secret.

299
00:23:05,080 --> 00:23:07,674
- Secret?
- Yes, a secret.

300
00:23:07,760 --> 00:23:12,914
At 12 o'clock today, the guards
at those doors will leave their posts

301
00:23:13,000 --> 00:23:16,436
and their replacements
are going to be five minutes late.

302
00:23:16,520 --> 00:23:18,590
Late five minutes.

303
00:23:18,680 --> 00:23:23,629
Yes. Late five minutes. At 12 o'clock.
Just today. Just this once.

304
00:23:23,720 --> 00:23:25,870
No one is going
to be watching those doors.

305
00:23:25,960 --> 00:23:30,431
- And no one will be watching you.
- So, America not closed.

306
00:23:30,520 --> 00:23:31,635
No.

307
00:23:31,720 --> 00:23:35,759
America, for five minutes, is open.

308
00:23:35,840 --> 00:23:37,876
Have a nice life, Mr. Navorski.

309
00:23:47,280 --> 00:23:50,590
Catch and release. It's simple.
Sometimes you land a small fish.

310
00:23:50,680 --> 00:23:53,638
You unhook him
and place him back in the water.

311
00:23:53,720 --> 00:23:58,316
You set him free so that somebody else
can have the pleasure of catching him.

312
00:24:01,320 --> 00:24:03,470
All right, here we go.

313
00:24:03,560 --> 00:24:05,755
OK. Call them off.

314
00:24:05,840 --> 00:24:08,035
Johnson, clear the doors.

315
00:24:10,960 --> 00:24:11,995
All right. Go.

316
00:24:12,080 --> 00:24:15,231
Get out of there.
All right, there's the door.

317
00:24:16,200 --> 00:24:17,918
All right.

318
00:24:18,000 --> 00:24:20,719
Here we go.
Now where is he?

319
00:24:20,800 --> 00:24:23,553
- There he is.
- No, that's not him.

320
00:24:23,640 --> 00:24:25,551
There he is.

321
00:24:25,640 --> 00:24:27,073
All right, Viktor.

322
00:24:27,800 --> 00:24:29,358
Here we go.

323
00:24:40,480 --> 00:24:42,391
[Whistle]

324
00:24:45,680 --> 00:24:49,355
What's so complicated? Exit, Viktor.

325
00:24:49,440 --> 00:24:52,750
Come on. In a few minutes,
you'll be somebody else's problem.

326
00:24:52,840 --> 00:24:54,956
He wants to make sure
nobody's watching.

327
00:24:55,040 --> 00:24:57,429
I told him nobody would be watching.

328
00:24:57,520 --> 00:25:00,830
Come on. All right, here we go.

329
00:25:00,920 --> 00:25:03,275
- Call the Airport Police.
- He's on his way.

330
00:25:04,880 --> 00:25:05,949
Excuse me.

331
00:25:11,960 --> 00:25:13,871
[Camera whirs]

332
00:25:25,520 --> 00:25:28,114
You got it. There we go.

333
00:25:28,200 --> 00:25:31,317
He's got to get a running start,
I guess.

334
00:25:31,400 --> 00:25:33,834
Just leave. Just leave.

335
00:25:33,920 --> 00:25:35,876
Leave. Leave.

336
00:25:35,960 --> 00:25:39,430
What are you doing?
Why is he kneeling? Is he praying?

337
00:25:39,520 --> 00:25:41,954
No. He's tying his shoelace.

338
00:25:47,280 --> 00:25:49,430
Come on, leave.

339
00:25:49,520 --> 00:25:51,431
Get the cameras.

340
00:25:58,040 --> 00:26:01,510
Where is he? Where is he?

341
00:26:05,880 --> 00:26:08,633
- [Thurman] To the left of here.
- No. He was at the door.

342
00:26:08,720 --> 00:26:11,598
- [Thurman] Just go a little left.
- All right. All right.

343
00:26:20,200 --> 00:26:21,633
I wait.

344
00:26:28,440 --> 00:26:31,591
What are you looking at?
Go back to work. Thank you.

345
00:26:37,320 --> 00:26:38,753
[Shrieks]

346
00:26:38,840 --> 00:26:41,877
[Woman] Oh, God. Oh, shit.

347
00:26:43,880 --> 00:26:45,836
[Speaks Bulgarian]

348
00:26:49,880 --> 00:26:52,838
- This belong you?
- Thank you.

349
00:26:52,920 --> 00:26:54,717
Oh, shit.

350
00:26:56,120 --> 00:26:59,237
See? Wet floor.

351
00:26:59,320 --> 00:27:00,878
That you.

352
00:27:00,960 --> 00:27:02,393
I'm so late.

353
00:27:02,480 --> 00:27:05,074
Buenos Aires.
I can't remember the gate.

354
00:27:05,160 --> 00:27:07,276
Gate 24.

355
00:27:07,360 --> 00:27:09,635
- You sure?
- Yes.

356
00:27:11,160 --> 00:27:12,878
Thanks.

357
00:27:12,960 --> 00:27:15,679
<i>[Tannoy] Ladies and gentlemen...</i>

358
00:27:15,760 --> 00:27:17,796
Wait.

359
00:27:17,880 --> 00:27:20,474
For you. Payless Shoes.

360
00:27:20,560 --> 00:27:23,028
Second floor.
Sensible heels.

361
00:27:35,600 --> 00:27:37,830
- Hi, baby.
- Come here, you.

362
00:27:43,760 --> 00:27:49,198
<i>[Gupta] I think he's CIA.
The CIA put him here to spy on us.</i>

363
00:27:49,280 --> 00:27:52,955
You don't know what you're talking
about. He doesn't speak English.

364
00:27:53,040 --> 00:27:55,395
If he could learn to speak, this guy.

365
00:27:55,480 --> 00:27:59,359
He can't speak English, how could he
have a meeting with a beautiful woman?

366
00:27:59,440 --> 00:28:00,714
A flight attendant.

367
00:28:00,800 --> 00:28:03,155
- So, she's CIA, too?
- No.

368
00:28:03,240 --> 00:28:08,712
She look like a Russian.
KGB. She gave him heel of her shoes.

369
00:28:08,800 --> 00:28:10,677
And he gave her a piece of the paper.

370
00:28:10,760 --> 00:28:15,117
- Was it microfilm?
- A coupon from Payless Shoes.

371
00:28:15,200 --> 00:28:17,589
Must be some kind of the code.

372
00:28:17,680 --> 00:28:22,356
You been spending too much time
inhaling them cleaning products.

373
00:28:22,440 --> 00:28:25,318
I'm warning you guys.
You watch yourself.

374
00:28:25,400 --> 00:28:30,190
This guy is here for a reason.
And I think that reason is us.

375
00:28:32,000 --> 00:28:33,911
<i>[Music plays]</i>

376
00:28:50,480 --> 00:28:51,754
Excuse me, buddy.

377
00:29:12,720 --> 00:29:14,153
What's going on?

378
00:29:14,240 --> 00:29:17,391
It's Navorski.
He's figured out the quarters.

379
00:29:33,800 --> 00:29:35,631
[Coins jangle]

380
00:29:40,800 --> 00:29:44,190
Good afternoon. Welcome to Burger King.
May I take your order?

381
00:29:47,600 --> 00:29:49,079
Keep the change.

382
00:30:08,960 --> 00:30:10,234
Excuse me.

383
00:30:14,920 --> 00:30:17,878
OK, go. Go.

384
00:30:19,840 --> 00:30:22,752
Good boy. Thank you.

385
00:30:23,800 --> 00:30:24,835
Bye-bye.

386
00:30:42,040 --> 00:30:44,508
Welcome to Burger King.
May I take your...

387
00:30:55,040 --> 00:30:56,951
<i>[TV: Brass band plays]</i>

388
00:31:10,160 --> 00:31:13,789
"Crisis. Crisis in Krakozhia."

389
00:31:13,880 --> 00:31:15,836
<i>Now that heavy fighting has subsided</i>

390
00:31:15,920 --> 00:31:18,832
<i>and both sides have dug in
for the long winter ahead,</i>

391
00:31:18,920 --> 00:31:23,118
<i>it's clear that the future of Krakozhia
may be in doubt for some time to come.</i>

392
00:31:23,200 --> 00:31:26,829
<i>Meanwhile, the people of Krakozhia
suffer the consequences.</i>

393
00:31:26,920 --> 00:31:29,992
"And food... in..."

394
00:31:30,080 --> 00:31:32,640
<i>... have caused food
and energy shortages.</i>

395
00:31:32,720 --> 00:31:34,631
"...in Krakozhia."

396
00:31:35,440 --> 00:31:36,839
[Shouts in Bulgarian]

397
00:31:52,480 --> 00:31:54,391
[Speaks Bulgarian]

398
00:31:56,240 --> 00:32:00,836
"The story of Broadway is the..."

399
00:32:05,400 --> 00:32:11,270
<i>"The cast of comedy hit Friends</i>

400
00:32:11,960 --> 00:32:15,555
which is set in New York."

401
00:32:16,440 --> 00:32:18,829
<i>[Speaks Bulgarian] Friends.</i>

402
00:32:18,920 --> 00:32:20,831
<i>[Speaks Bulgarian] Friends.</i>

403
00:32:28,240 --> 00:32:31,869
<i>[Tannoy] Due to the heavy snowfall,
all flights have been cancelled...</i>

404
00:32:31,960 --> 00:32:33,871
[all groan]

405
00:32:39,400 --> 00:32:41,311
[Viktor speaks Bulgarian]

406
00:32:41,840 --> 00:32:45,515
"Wayne Newton is 61 today."

407
00:32:45,600 --> 00:32:47,511
"It's a miracle."

408
00:32:48,840 --> 00:32:53,550
"Korean conjoined twins
separated today in Maine."

409
00:32:53,640 --> 00:32:56,916
"Chances of survival 50-50."

410
00:32:57,000 --> 00:32:58,194
50-50.

411
00:33:01,880 --> 00:33:04,030
Next.

412
00:33:05,520 --> 00:33:07,670
Let me ask you something,
Mr. Navorski.

413
00:33:07,760 --> 00:33:11,196
Why do you wait here every day
when there's nothing I can do for you?

414
00:33:11,280 --> 00:33:17,071
Your new visa will not arrive until
your country is recognized by the US.

415
00:33:17,160 --> 00:33:19,116
You have two stamp.

416
00:33:19,200 --> 00:33:22,033
One red, one green.

417
00:33:22,120 --> 00:33:27,353
- So?
- I have chance to go New York, 50-50.

418
00:33:27,440 --> 00:33:29,351
[Chuckles]

419
00:33:30,880 --> 00:33:34,793
Yes. That's a beautiful way to look at
it, but America doesn't work that way.

420
00:33:48,560 --> 00:33:52,951
As acting Field Commissioner,
I've created a new position here at JFK.

421
00:33:53,040 --> 00:33:57,192
Transportation Liaison
for Passenger Assistance.

422
00:33:58,000 --> 00:34:01,231
Sir, what will that person do?

423
00:34:04,560 --> 00:34:05,754
[Shrieks]

424
00:34:05,840 --> 00:34:08,752
Thank you.
I'll take it from here.

425
00:34:10,920 --> 00:34:14,549
I'm Transportation Liaison
in charge of Passenger Assistance.

426
00:34:22,840 --> 00:34:25,195
No carts, no quarters.
No quarters, no food.

427
00:34:25,280 --> 00:34:29,637
It'll be days before he goes through
the doors in violation of section 2.14

428
00:34:29,720 --> 00:34:31,597
Then he's somebody else's problem.

429
00:34:31,680 --> 00:34:34,672
Why don't we tag him
in violation of section 2.14 now?

430
00:34:34,760 --> 00:34:36,193
Then ship him to detention.

431
00:34:36,280 --> 00:34:38,316
He has to break the law by leaving.

432
00:34:38,400 --> 00:34:41,676
I won't lie, particularly to get rid
of somebody like him.

433
00:34:41,760 --> 00:34:43,671
<i>[Country music plays]</i>

434
00:35:16,400 --> 00:35:18,755
- [Max] Sorry, buddy.
- Honey!

435
00:35:40,600 --> 00:35:43,034
Put it down. Put it down.

436
00:35:44,400 --> 00:35:46,311
Put it down.

437
00:35:47,280 --> 00:35:50,795
You try to take my mop.
You try to take my floor.

438
00:35:50,880 --> 00:35:55,078
It's my job. Stay off my floor.
Stay away from my mop.

439
00:35:55,160 --> 00:35:57,754
- Food.
- If you touch it again, I kill you.

440
00:36:00,360 --> 00:36:02,351
[Shrieks]

441
00:36:08,240 --> 00:36:10,151
[Light switch]

442
00:36:11,400 --> 00:36:13,630
Hey. I'm Enrique Cruz.

443
00:36:16,920 --> 00:36:18,831
We need to talk.

444
00:36:23,000 --> 00:36:26,436
- I want to make a deal with you.
- What deal?

445
00:36:26,520 --> 00:36:29,717
I need information
on CBP Officer Torres.

446
00:36:29,800 --> 00:36:32,712
You feed me information about her
and I'll feed you.

447
00:36:32,800 --> 00:36:36,110
- What do you want know?
- You see her every day.

448
00:36:36,200 --> 00:36:40,671
I want to know
what makes her knees weak.

449
00:36:40,760 --> 00:36:45,709
What makes her blood boil
and her body tingle.

450
00:36:45,800 --> 00:36:48,951
She's a wild stallion
and you'll help me break her.

451
00:36:49,040 --> 00:36:50,473
I'm...

452
00:36:50,560 --> 00:36:52,630
I'm her man of mystery.

453
00:36:52,720 --> 00:36:57,475
- Officer Torres is wild stallion?
- Her name is Delores.

454
00:36:57,560 --> 00:37:01,348
You help me to win her heart
and you'll never go hungry again.

455
00:37:03,680 --> 00:37:06,148
- I do this.
- Really? Promise?

456
00:37:06,240 --> 00:37:09,357
- Yes.
- OK. Thank you.

457
00:37:10,080 --> 00:37:12,389
What mean, "wild stallion"?

458
00:37:17,720 --> 00:37:19,153
[Speaks Bulgarian]

459
00:37:19,240 --> 00:37:22,676
Officer Torres.
My friend say you are stallion.

460
00:37:22,760 --> 00:37:24,671
Mr. Navorski.

461
00:37:24,760 --> 00:37:27,558
- A what?
- Stallion, like a horse.

462
00:37:27,640 --> 00:37:29,631
Stand behind the yellow line.

463
00:37:29,720 --> 00:37:32,359
- It's beautiful horse.
- Who said that?

464
00:37:32,440 --> 00:37:37,355
- My friend drive the food.
- Mr. Navorski, behind the yellow line.

465
00:37:37,440 --> 00:37:40,398
- I will help once it's your turn.
- I'll get light green.

466
00:37:40,480 --> 00:37:43,597
- Light green form.
- I'll be back.

467
00:37:45,520 --> 00:37:47,511
Mm.

468
00:37:47,600 --> 00:37:49,511
She say one thing.

469
00:37:51,720 --> 00:37:55,838
- Very important.
- What? What did she tell you?

470
00:37:58,080 --> 00:37:59,832
Something wrong with the salmon?

471
00:37:59,920 --> 00:38:01,558
<i>Need gorchitsa.</i>

472
00:38:01,640 --> 00:38:02,789
What?

473
00:38:03,960 --> 00:38:04,995
Mustard. Mustard?

474
00:38:05,080 --> 00:38:07,799
- Mustard?
- Yes. Please.

475
00:38:11,840 --> 00:38:13,751
Thank you.

476
00:38:21,560 --> 00:38:24,279
Officer Torres, you like the films?

477
00:38:24,360 --> 00:38:26,590
- Movies?
- Not so much.

478
00:38:26,680 --> 00:38:29,752
- The Rockettes?
- Can't afford it.

479
00:38:29,840 --> 00:38:32,195
- What do you like?
- Conventions.

480
00:38:33,640 --> 00:38:35,756
Conventions. What is?

481
00:38:35,840 --> 00:38:40,277
- Conventions.
- Conventions?

482
00:38:40,360 --> 00:38:42,316
This is like secret place you go?

483
00:38:43,120 --> 00:38:48,831
She go to these conventions
dressed as Yeoman Rand.

484
00:38:48,920 --> 00:38:50,797
- Yeoman Rand.
- She's a Trekkie.

485
00:38:50,880 --> 00:38:53,872
<i>Favorite episode
is Doomsday Machine.</i>

486
00:38:53,960 --> 00:38:55,871
[Speaks Spanish]

487
00:38:59,400 --> 00:39:00,799
Now, listen, Viktor.

488
00:39:00,880 --> 00:39:03,348
You can ask her something
